an Bourgeoisie -- tBodies Of Illusion: Portraits, People, And The Construction Of Memory -- tA Criminal Is Being Beaten: The Politics Of Punishment And The History Of The Body -- tPart Four: Oral Performance, Personal Power -- tMassacred Language: Courtroom Performance In Eighteenth-Century Boston -- t"Neither Male Nor Female": Jemima Wilkinson And The Politics Of Gender In Post-Revolutionary America -- tThe Genders Of Nationalism: Patriotic Violence, Patriotic Sentiment In The Performances Of Deborah Sampson Gannett -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPossible Pasts represents a landmark in early American studies, bringing to that field the theoretical richness and innovative potential of the scholarship on colonial discourse and postcolonial theory. Drawing on the methods and interpretive insights of history, anthropology, history of art, folklore, and textual analysis, its authors explore the cultural processes by which individuals and societies become colonial.Rather than define early America in terms of conventional geographical, chronological, or subdisciplinary boundaries, their essays span landscapes from New England to Peru, time periods from the sixteenth to the mid-nineteenth century, and topics from religion to race and novels to nationalism. In his introduction Robert Blair St. George offers an overview of the genealogy of ideas and key terms appearing in the book.Part I, "Interrogating America," then challenges readers to rethink the meaning of "early America" and its relation to postcolonial theory. In Part II, "Translation and Transculturation," essays explore how both Europeans and native peoples viewed such concepts as dissent, witchcraft, family piety, and race. The construction of individual identity and agency in Philadelphia is the focus of Part III, "Shaping Subjectivities." Finally, Part IV, "Oral Performance and Personal Power," considers the ways in which political authority and gendered resistance were established in early America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh1 aBurkhart, Louise M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDitz, Toby L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Robert Blair St., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafson, Sandra M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, David D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulme, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuster, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovell, Margaretta M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazzotti, José Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeranze, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Laura J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyles, Anne G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Dana D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilverblatt, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith-Rosenberg, Carroll, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSt. George, Robert Blair, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThornton, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarner, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook 